# Never Put Credentials on the Command Line

**Hard rule. No exceptions.**

Do NOT type, paste, or interpolate a credential value (AD password,
API token, PAT, secret key, basic-auth string) into any shell command,
script invocation, or external tool argument. Anything that lands in
*argv* of a spawned process is captured by Windows process auditing
(Event ID 4688), Sysmon, Defender for Endpoint / Defender for Identity,
WMI `Win32_Process.CommandLine`, and is visible to **anyone** who can run
`Get-Process | Select CommandLine` or `wmic process get commandline` on
this host. Synopsys security scans for exactly this — Leslie has been
flagged for it.

## The non-obvious case: variable expansion still leaks

PowerShell expands `$env:VAR` and `$($env:VAR)` **before** calling
`CreateProcess`. That means:

```powershell
curl.exe -u "$($env:ADO_Username):$($env:ADO_Password)" $url
```

is **just as leaky** as a literal-typed password. By the time `curl.exe`
is spawned, its argv contains the actual `SYNOPSYS\ldove:RealPassword`
string. WMI sees it. EDR sees it.

**The variable-vs-literal source distinction does NOT matter for external
processes.** What matters is whether the credential ends up in argv of
something the OS spawns. If the call goes through a PowerShell cmdlet
(`Invoke-RestMethod`, `Invoke-WebRequest`) that runs in-process, no
spawn happens and the credential never hits any argv.

## What you MUST NOT do

External-process credential exposure (PowerShell expands variables before
`CreateProcess`, so var refs leak just like literals):

- `curl -u alice:hunter2 https://...`
- `curl -u "$env:ADO_Username:$env:ADO_Password" https://...` ← still leaks
- `curl.exe --ntlm -u "$($env:ADO_Username):$($env:ADO_Password)" $url` ← still leaks
- `curl --user user:pass https://...`, `curl --http-user X --http-password Y`
- `wget --user $env:U --password $env:P https://...` ← still leaks
- `git clone https://user:pass@host/repo.git`
- `git clone "https://$($env:GH_USER):$($env:GH_TOKEN)@github.com/..."` ← still leaks
- `az login --username X --password Y`
- `net use \\server\share <pw> /user:DOMAIN\user`
- `psexec \\host -u user -p <pw>`
- `sshpass -p <pw> ssh ...`
- `mysql -u user -p<pw>` or `--password=<pw>`
- `openssl ... -passin pass:<pw>`

Hardcoded credentials in script bodies (these end up on cmdline whenever
the script is invoked):

- `$env:GH_TOKEN = "ghp_literalstring"; gh ...`
- `$env:ADO_Password = "literalpassword"; ...`
- `set GIT_PASSWORD=literalpassword & git push ...`
- Hard-coded `Authorization: Basic <literal-base64>` in any `-H` / `--header` argument

Other:

- Pasting a token from a doc, vault, or 1Password directly into a command
- Any command that contains a verbatim value from `~/.env` for a key matching
  `*PASSWORD*` / `*TOKEN*` / `*SECRET*` / `*KEY*` / `*CREDENTIAL*` / `*AUTH*`

The hook `gate-credential-leak.ps1` blocks all of these.

## What you MUST do instead

**Stay in PowerShell.** Use cmdlets (`Invoke-RestMethod`, `Invoke-WebRequest`)
that run in-process — they never spawn a child process, so credentials
in `[PSCredential]` objects never hit any argv.

For ADO calls (the most common case in this repo), use the shared helper:

```powershell
. "$env:USERPROFILE\.cursor\lib\Ado-Auth.ps1"
$wi = Invoke-AdoRest -Uri "$baseUrl/_apis/wit/workitems/$id?api-version=6.0"
$pr = Invoke-AdoRest -Uri "$baseUrl/_apis/git/.../pullrequests?api-version=6.0" `
        -Method Post -Body $prBody
Invoke-AdoRest -Uri $url -OutFile 'C:\GitRepos\.scratch\foo.json'
```

`Invoke-AdoRest` wraps `Invoke-RestMethod -Credential <PSCredential>` with
the `~/.env` credential pre-loaded. NTLM negotiates in-process via .NET's
HttpClient. No spawn, no argv exposure.

For non-ADO endpoints, build the credential the same way:

```powershell
$secPw = ConvertTo-SecureString $env:SOMETHING_TOKEN -AsPlainText -Force
$cred  = [PSCredential]::new($env:SOMETHING_USER, $secPw)
$resp  = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri $url -Credential $cred
```

For Authorization headers built in-script:

```powershell
$pair    = "$($env:ADO_Username):$($env:ADO_Password)"
$basic   = [Convert]::ToBase64String([Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes($pair))
$headers = @{ Authorization = "Basic $basic" }
Invoke-RestMethod -Uri $url -Headers $headers @restArgs
```

Note: this is fine because everything is inside one PowerShell pipeline.
The base64 string never gets passed as an argument to a *spawned* process.

For git, use the Git Credential Manager (already configured on this host).
Don't embed creds in URLs — even via variables, expansion happens before
`CreateProcess` for `git.exe`.

For `az`, use `az login` interactively or a service-principal cred file
referenced by path, never `--password <value>`.

## How the hook decides

The hook treats any of these as a "variable reference" (allowed):

- `$env:FOO` (PowerShell environment variable)
- `${FOO}` or `$FOO` (PowerShell scalar variable)
- `%FOO%` (cmd.exe environment variable)
- A `$(...)` subexpression

A "literal" (denied) is anything else in the credential slot — bare
alphanumeric, base64, hex, etc.

If a pattern is matched, the hook returns `permission=deny` with a
specific remediation message. The denied command, with secrets redacted,
is logged to `~/.cursor/bot/sessions/credential-leak.log`.

## If the hook is wrong

If a real false positive happens (the value really is a non-secret token,
a public URL, or a test fixture), rephrase so the credential slot is
clearly variable-referenced and retry. If you genuinely need to bypass
the hook (you almost never do), **stop and ask Leslie first** — do not
edit the hook to add an exception unilaterally.

## Background

Added 2026-05-28 after Synopsys security flagged that an agent had run a
command exposing Leslie's AD credentials. Leslie rotated her password
immediately.

Initial investigation: a hook was added that blocked literal credential
values on the command line. That caught the obvious shape but not the
real one. A controlled WMI sweep then confirmed the root cause — every
auth'd skill call used:

```
curl.exe -s --ntlm -u "$($env:ADO_Username):$($env:ADO_Password)" <url>
```

PowerShell expands the env vars before calling `CreateProcess`, so the
literal password lands in `curl.exe`'s argv, where Defender for Endpoint /
Sysmon / WMI all see it. This had been happening on every ADO API call
since the skills were written.

Fix on 2026-05-28:

1. New shared helper `~/.cursor/lib/Ado-Auth.ps1` provides `Get-AdoCredential`
   and `Invoke-AdoRest` (`Invoke-RestMethod -Credential` wrapper). NTLM
   auth happens in-process; no `curl.exe` spawn.
2. All skill files migrated: `ado`, `ado-doc`, `ado-release-docs`,
   `corp-doc-showcase`, `sprint-review`, `flo`. Stale tmp helper scripts
   in `~/.cursor/bot/tmp/` deleted (they get regenerated by skill runs).
3. `~/.cursor/dashboard/generate-dashboard.ps1` migrated.
4. Hook `gate-credential-leak.ps1` tightened: now blocks `curl.exe -u`
   and `wget --user`/`--password` regardless of whether the value is a
   literal or a variable reference, because the var-expansion case still
   leaks to argv.

